  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contracting in Georgia through FY2026 to date shows $6.1B in contract obligations across 53,580 awards with an average award size of $114K; obligations are down 47.7% year over year. Yearly obligations by fiscal year show prior totals of $11.1B in FY21, $8.5B in FY22, $11B in FY23, $10.4B in FY24, and $11.6B in FY25, with the current fiscal-year-to-date total at $6.1B. The Department of Defense accounts for the largest share of buying-agency obligations at $3.3B, followed by the Department of Health and Human Services at $991M and the General Services Administration at $727M. Top vendor awards include LOCKHEED MARTIN CORP at $551M and MANHATTAN TORCON A JOINT VENTURE at $492M. Major industry concentrations by NAICS are Commercial and Institutional Building Construction at $918M, Aircraft Manufacturing at $619M, and Engineering Services at $498M. All figures are contract obligations; current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date).",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies are the largest buyers in Georgia?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense is the largest buyer with $3.3B in obligations. Other top buying agencies are the Department of Health and Human Services ($991M) and the General Services Administration ($727M). The Department of Homeland Security ($274M), Department of Agriculture ($220M), and Department of Veterans Affairs ($210M) round out the mid-tier buyers."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Who captures the most federal contract dollars in Georgia?",
        "body": "LOCKHEED MARTIN CORP is the largest vendor by obligations at $551M, followed by MANHATTAN TORCON A JOINT VENTURE at $492M. Additional leading contractors include BOOZ ALLEN HAMILTON INC ($173M), PERATON INC. ($151M), and GEORGIA TECH APPLIED RESEARCH CORP ($146M)."
      }
    ]
